description:
In generate_eui64(), the bounds check for hwid_len happens AFTER hwinfo_get_device_id() has already written to the buffer:

```c
hwid_len = hwinfo_get_device_id(hwid, sizeof(hwid));
if (hwid_len <= 0) {
    ...
    return -ENODEV;
}
if ((size_t)hwid_len > sizeof(hwid)) {
    LOG_ERR("hwinfo returned invalid length: %d", (int)hwid_len);
    return -EINVAL;
}
```

If hwinfo_get_device_id() returns a length greater than sizeof(hwid), it indicates the driver has ALREADY overflowed the buffer. The bounds check detects the condition but cannot undo the corruption.

Impact: This is defense-in-depth logging, not a fix. The actual bug would be in the hwinfo driver. The check is correct to have, but the damage (if any) has already occurred.

This is a detection-only guard, which is the right thing to do. The code cannot prevent a misbehaving driver from overwriting the buffer - it can only detect the condition and refuse to proceed. The existing code is correct.

Closing as no action needed - the code correctly handles this edge case by refusing to continue.
